                            <comment id="20552" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Mon, 30 Oct 2006 20:09:22 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This is a general issue with J2EE class loading if you deploy Spring in the EJB tier as well as in the web tier. The underlying root cause is that the Servlet API is usually not present in the EJB class loader, but some Spring classes that might be deployed there do (optionally) refer to the Servlet API.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As you pointed out, a couple of jar files would have to be split up into finer-grained pieces in order to address this issue. Since we do not plan to change the deployment layout for the present Spring branches, this is scheduled to be revisited for Spring 2.1.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="24034" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Sun, 27 May 2007 19:21:05 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;As of Spring 2.1 M2, the module jar files have been rearranged, with spring-orm.jar now containing the entire base ORM support and spring-web.jar containing the web-related ORM classes. Note that the underlying packages are still the same base; it&apos;s just the specific jar file contents that changed.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
